git remote add origin https://github.com/<your-username>/hello-java.git

tells Git where your local repository should be connected on GitHub.

Let's break it down:

git

Runs the Git program.

remote

A remote is another copy of your repository, usually hosted on a server like GitHub.

Your local repository is on your computer. The remote repository is on GitHub.

add

Adds a new remote.

origin

origin is just a name (an alias) for the remote repository.

You could name it anything:

git remote add github https://github.com/username/hello-java.git

or

git remote add myrepo https://github.com/username/hello-java.git

But almost everyone uses origin, so Git commands assume that's the main remote.

https://github.com/<your-username>/hello-java.git

This is the URL of your GitHub repository.

For example, if your GitHub username is johnsmith, it becomes:

git remote add origin https://github.com/johnsmith/hello-java.git
What happens after this?

Your local Git repository now knows where the GitHub repository is.

You can verify it:

git remote -v

Example output:

origin  https://github.com/johnsmith/hello-java.git (fetch)
origin  https://github.com/johnsmith/hello-java.git (push)
fetch: Download changes from GitHub.
push: Upload your commits to GitHub.
Why is this needed?

Before adding a remote:

Your Computer
┌───────────────┐
│ hello-java    │
│ Git repository│
└───────────────┘

After adding the remote:

Your Computer                     GitHub
┌───────────────┐            ┌─────────────────────┐
│ hello-java    │──────────▶│ hello-java          │
│ Git repository│  origin   │ Remote repository   │
└───────────────┘            └─────────────────────┘

Git stores this connection so later you can simply run:

git push

or

git pull

without typing the full GitHub URL each time.

----------

git fetch and git pull are related, but they do different things.

Command	Downloads changes	Updates your local branch	Safe?
git fetch	✅ Yes	❌ No	✅ Very safe
git pull	✅ Yes	✅ Yes	⚠️ May cause merge conflicts
1. git fetch
git fetch

This downloads new commits from the remote repository (GitHub), but does not change your working files or current branch.

Example

Suppose GitHub has one new commit.

Before fetch:

GitHub (origin/main)
A --- B --- C

Local (main)
A --- B

Run:

git fetch

After fetch:

GitHub (origin/main)
A --- B --- C

Local (main)
A --- B

Remote-tracking branch
origin/main
A --- B --- C

Notice:

Your local main is still at B.
Git now knows that origin/main is at C.

You can inspect the new commit before updating your branch.

Useful commands after fetching:

git log main..origin/main

or

git diff main origin/main
2. git pull
git pull

git pull is equivalent to:

git fetch
git merge

It downloads the changes and immediately merges them into your current branch.

Example:

Before:

GitHub
A --- B --- C

Local
A --- B

Run:

git pull

After:

GitHub
A --- B --- C

Local
A --- B --- C

Your local branch is now updated automatically.

If both you and GitHub have new commits

Suppose:

GitHub
A --- B --- C

Local
A --- B --- D
git fetch

After fetching:

main
A --- B --- D

origin/main
A --- B --- C

Nothing changes in your current branch. You can decide how to combine the histories.

git pull

Git tries to merge automatically:

      C
     /
A---B
     \
      D
       \
        M

If both commits modify the same lines, Git may report a merge conflict, which you'll need to resolve before completing the merge.

Which should you use?
Use git fetch when you want to see what's new before updating your branch. This is common in larger teams because it lets you review incoming changes first.
Use git pull when you simply want to bring your local branch up to date and you're comfortable with Git merging the changes automatically.
Easy way to remember
Fetch = Download only
Pull = Download + Merge

A good habit is:

git fetch
git log --oneline main..origin/main

Review the incoming changes, then update with:

git merge origin/main

or, if you prefer a single command:

git pull

This gives you more control over when and how your local branch changes.

--------------

git log main..origin/main
git diff main origin/main

These commands compare your local branch (main) with the remote-tracking branch (origin/main).

Think of them like this:

main = your local copy.
origin/main = your local record of what's on GitHub (updated by git fetch).
1. git log main..origin/main
git log main..origin/main

This shows commits that are in origin/main but NOT in main.

Suppose:

Local (main)

A --- B


GitHub (origin/main)

A --- B --- C --- D

After git fetch:

main
A --- B

origin/main
A --- B --- C --- D

Run:

git log main..origin/main

Output:

commit D
Author: Alice
Message: Fix login bug

commit C
Author: Bob
Message: Add payment feature

Git is saying:

"These commits exist on GitHub but you don't have them yet."

Reverse it
git log origin/main..main

Now Git shows commits you have locally but haven't pushed.

Example:

main
A --- B --- C

origin/main
A --- B

Output:

commit C
Message: Add README

This is useful before running git push.

2. git diff main origin/main

git diff compares the actual file contents.

Suppose:

Local HelloWorld.java

System.out.println("Hello");

GitHub version

System.out.println("Hello World!");

Run:

git diff main origin/main

Output:

-System.out.println("Hello");
+System.out.println("Hello World!");

Unlike git log, which shows commits, git diff shows the code changes.

An easy analogy

Imagine writing a Word document.

git log

Shows revision history.

Revision 10
- Added login page

Revision 11
- Fixed bug

You see what changes were made and who made them.

git diff

Shows the document itself with highlighted edits.

- Hello
+ Hello World!

You see exactly which lines changed.

---------

Command	Purpose	Shows
git log main..origin/main	Compare commit history	Commits on GitHub that you don't have locally
git log origin/main..main	Compare commit history	Commits you have locally that aren't on GitHub
git diff main origin/main	Compare file contents	The exact line-by-line code differences
git fetch	Update remote-tracking branches	Downloads the latest GitHub state without changing your working files

